article.headline: Sparks not slowed by injuries, fouls
article.linkText: Sparks win in Cleveland for league-best 17-4 record
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Mwadi Mabika's finger was a little crooked, but her shot stayed pretty straight. Mabika scored 13 of her 15 points after dislocating an index finger, and Lisa Leslie had 14 before fouling out with a sore ankle to lead the Los Angeles Sparks to a 63-50 win Saturday over the Cleveland Rockers. Mabika played only four minutes in the first half when she dislocated the finger on her shooting hand while on defense. But the Sparks' leading scorer returned after halftime with it taped and scored 11 points in a seven-minute span when Los Angeles blew it open. "They popped it back into place,'' Mabika said. "I was hoping I wouldn't have to shoot very much with it.'' Mabika didn't, but made 5-of-8 attempts from the floor in the second half and two free throws. "She stepped up for us,'' Leslie said. "She was afraid to shoot because of her finger. And we were like, 'Wadi, still go strong'. She did a great job of getting me the ball inside and taking control of the game.'' Leslie, MVP of the WNBA's All-Star game earlier this week, fouled out with 7:46 remaining, but by then the Sparks had opened a 19-point lead. Los Angeles improved to a league-best 17-4. Rookie Nikki Teasley had 14 points, seven rebounds and eight assists for the Sparks, who went 3-2 on a five-game road trip and were coming off a 13-point loss in New York. "This was an important win for us because of the game in New York,'' Mabika said. "We needed this game so bad after that loss. I can't wait to get home.'' The Rockers shot just 26 percent from the floor and lost their fourth straight home game. Cleveland was just 7-for-31 from the field in the second half. Penny Taylor scored 11 points -- on 3-of-14 shooting -- to lead Cleveland, and Merlakia Jones had 9 with a 4-for-18 performance. The 5-foot-9 Jones led the cold-shooting Rockers with nine rebounds. Cleveland's starters went 11-for-48 and the Rockers were only 2-for-24 during a stretch when the Sparks turned a five-point deficit into a 20-point lead. "We made them take tough shots, but offensively, we couldn't get anything going,'' said Rockers guard Jennifer Rizzotti. "And that really hurt us in the second half when they started to pull away, we started to force some things.'' Leslie and Mabika, also an All-Star, scored four points apiece in a 13-0 run that helped the Sparks go ahead 42-27 with 12:10 left. And although they didn't have to worry about a Cleveland comeback, the Sparks did get a scare during the spurt when Leslie rolled her right ankle going after a loose ball with 15:19 to go. She returned one minute later, but was soon back on the bench after picking up her fifth personal foul. Leslie returned with about eight minutes left and Los Angeles ahead 51-32, but she fouled out seconds later. The Rockers led 23-18 in the first half before making five turnovers and missing six straight shots as the Sparks scored seven straight points to lead 25-23 at the break.

Game notes
Cleveland's shooting performance was the second worst in club history. The Rockers shot 24 percent in a July 8, 1999, loss to New York. ... Mabika has made 28 straight free throws. ... Leslie said her ankle is sore, but OK. ... Mabika as led the Sparks in scoring 10 times this season. ... Los Angeles is 4-4 after starting the season 12-1.
